# Proper Error Handling - Best Practices

Here are the key principles for handling errors properly:

## 1. **Try-Catch Blocks**
```javascript
try {
  // Code that might throw an error
  riskyOperation();
} catch (error) {
  // Handle the error
  console.error('An error occurred:', error.message);
} finally {
  // Cleanup code (optional)
  cleanup();
}
```

## 2. **Specific Error Types**
```javascript
try {
  validateInput(data);
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof TypeError) {
    console.error('Type error:', error.message);
  } else if (error instanceof RangeError) {
    console.error('Range error:', error.message);
  } else {
    console.error('Unknown error:', error);
  }
}
```

## 3. **Async/Await Error Handling**
```javascript
async function fetchData(url) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url);
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }
    return await response.json();
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Fetch error:', error.message);
    // Return default value or rethrow
    throw error;
  }
}
```

## 4. **Custom Error Classes**
```javascript
class ValidationError extends Error {
  constructor(message) {
    super(message);
    this.name = 'ValidationError';
  }
}

try {
  throw new ValidationError('Invalid input');
} catch (error) {
  console.error(`${error.name}: ${error.message}`);
}
```

## 5. **Promise Error Handling**
```javascript
promise
  .then(result => console.log(result))
  .catch(error => console.error('Promise error:', error))
  .finally(() => console.log('Done'));
```

## 6. **Error Logging Best Practices**
- ✅ Log the full error object
- ✅ Include context information
- ✅ Use appropriate log levels (error, warn, info)
- ✅ Don't expose sensitive information to users

